title: wdiexplorer
text: load WDI indicator data choice, function get_wdi_data() designed retrieve data WDI R package. get_wdi_data() function takes single argument named indicator, valid code (e.g., vignette, using PM2.5 air pollution data WDI indicator code: “EN.ATM.PM25.MC.M3”). can find indicator codes using WDI::WDISearch() function R, illustrated .
code: WDI::WDIsearch("air pollution") #>               indicator #> 3036     CC.SH.AIRP.AIR #> 3037     CC.SH.AIRP.AMB #> 7048  EN.ATM.PM25.MC.M3 #> 7052  EN.ATM.PM25.MC.ZS #> 21363 SH.STA.AIRP.FE.P5 #> 21364 SH.STA.AIRP.MA.P5 #> 21365    SH.STA.AIRP.P5 #>                                                                                                                             name #> 3036                                      Mortality rate attributable to household air pollution (deaths per 100 000 population) #> 3037                                        Mortality rate attributable to ambient air pollution (deaths per 100 000 population) #> 7048                                                      PM2.5 air pollution, mean annual exposure (micrograms per cubic meter) #> 7052                                PM2.5 air pollution, population exposed to levels exceeding WHO guideline value (% of total) #> 21363 Mortality rate attributed to household and ambient air pollution, age-standardized, female (per 100,000 female population) #> 21364     Mortality rate attributed to household and ambient air pollution, age-standardized, male (per 100,000 male population) #> 21365                Mortality rate attributed to household and ambient air pollution, age-standardized (per 100,000 population)  # use the get_wdi_data() function to fetch the data set from the WDI pm_data <- get_wdi_data(indicator = "EN.ATM.PM25.MC.M3") #> Loading WDI indicator: EN.ATM.PM25.MC.M3 data from data folder.  tibble::glimpse(pm_data) #> Rows: 14,040 #> Columns: 13 #> $ country           <chr> "Afghanistan", "Afghanistan", "Afghanistan", "Afghan… #> $ iso2c             <chr> "AF", "AF", "AF", "AF", "AF", "AF", "AF", "AF", "AF"… #> $ iso3c             <chr> "AFG", "AFG", "AFG", "AFG", "AFG", "AFG", "AFG", "AF… #> $ year              <int> 2013, 2012, 2014, 2009, 2008, 2007, 2006, 2005, 2004… #> $ EN.ATM.PM25.MC.M3 <dbl> 73.13182, 70.92232, 77.14373, 51.00144, 54.19114, 58… #> $ status            <chr> "", "", "", "", "", "", "", "", "", "", "", "", "", … #> $ lastupdated       <chr> "2025-07-01", "2025-07-01", "2025-07-01", "2025-07-0… #> $ region            <chr> "South Asia", "South Asia", "South Asia", "South Asi… #> $ capital           <chr> "Kabul", "Kabul", "Kabul", "Kabul", "Kabul", "Kabul"… #> $ longitude         <chr> "69.1761", "69.1761", "69.1761", "69.1761", "69.1761… #> $ latitude          <chr> "34.5228", "34.5228", "34.5228", "34.5228", "34.5228… #> $ income            <chr> "Low income", "Low income", "Low income", "Low incom… #> $ lending           <chr> "IDA", "IDA", "IDA", "IDA", "IDA", "IDA", "IDA", "ID…

title: wdiexplorer
text: second stage workflow focuses calculating diagnostic indices. measure variation, trend shape features, well sequential temporal characteristics.

title: wdiexplorer
text: measure variation, compute_variation() function accepts two main arguments: data set WDI indicator grouping variable group_var. also includes optional dissimilarity matrix argument, diss_matrix (defaulting output compute_dissimilarity(). compute_dissimilarity() function takes data set WDI indicator, returns matrix dissimilarity values country pairs. Users can compute dissimilarity matrix separately pass directly diss_matrix argument compute_variation() function demonstrated allow function compute internally specifying two main arguments. output pm_variation enables exploration computed variation features. facilitates identification distinctive countries, evaluation within-group differences, analysis closely aligned countries within group compared groups. However, measures always intuitive interpret ; best understood conjunction accompanying data series trajectories.
code: pm_diss_mat <- compute_dissimilarity(pm_data)   pm_variation <- compute_variation(                     pm_data,                      diss_matrix = pm_diss_mat,                      group_var = "region"         )

title: wdiexplorer
text: result shows Qatar highest overall average dissimilarity, followed Niger Mauritania. countries, Qatar, Niger, Mauritania, rank highest overall average dissimilarity also exhibit highest dissimilarity relative countries respective region groups.
code: pm_variation |>          dplyr::arrange(desc(country_avg_dist)) |>          dplyr::slice_head(n = 3) #> # A tibble: 3 × 5 #>   country    group              country_avg_dist within_group_avg_dist sil_width #>   <chr>      <chr>                         <dbl>                 <dbl>     <dbl> #> 1 Qatar      Middle East & Nor…             498.                  410.    -0.168 #> 2 Niger      Sub-Saharan Africa             478.                  408.    -0.207 #> 3 Mauritania Sub-Saharan Africa             414.                  345.    -0.243

title: wdiexplorer
text: examine trend shape features, compute_trend_shape_features() takes one main argument: dataset WDI indicator data additional index argument defaults NULL. returns data frame containing columns: country, trend_strength, linearity, smoothness. pm_trend_shape output enables exploration computed trend shape features. output highlights countries strongest trends. Ukraine, Moldova, United Kingdom top three countries strongest trend strength.
code: pm_trend_shape <- compute_trend_shape_features(pm_data) #> Registered S3 method overwritten by 'tsibble': #>   method               from  #>   as_tibble.grouped_df dplyr pm_trend_shape |>          dplyr::arrange(desc(trend_strength)) |>     dplyr::slice_head(n = 3) #> # A tibble: 3 × 5 #>   country        trend_strength linearity curvature smoothness #>   <chr>                   <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>      <dbl> #> 1 Ukraine                 0.996     -32.4     2.69       0.547 #> 2 Moldova                 0.995     -34.4     2.65       0.666 #> 3 United Kingdom          0.995     -16.3    -0.217      0.329

title: wdiexplorer
text: Lastly, measure sequential temporal features data series, compute_temporal_features() also takes arguments functions calculate diagnostic indices. returns data frame containing columns: country, crossing_points, flat_spot, autocorrelation. pm_temporal output enables exploration computed sequential temporal features. Kyrgyz Republic United Arab Emirates longest flat spots, characterised long consecutive periods data series remain within interval. contrast, Jordan, Rwanda, West Bank Gaza exhibit shortest consecutive periods series remain within specified interval. introduce function compute set diagnostic indices collectively returns measures single data frame. compute_diagnostic_indices() function takes two arguments: dataset WDI indicator data grouping variable group_var. pm_diagnostic_metrics output can passed directly plot functions wdiexplorer package. plot function requires grouping variable. Hence, introduce add_group_info() function append pre-defined grouping information WDI data set data frame computed diagnostics function output. function takes two arguments: data frame calculated diagnostic indices metric_summary; dataset WDI indicator data.
code: pm_temporal <- compute_temporal_features(pm_data) pm_temporal |>     dplyr::arrange(desc(flat_spot)) |>     dplyr::slice(c(1:3, (dplyr::n() - 2):dplyr::n())) #> # A tibble: 6 × 4 #>   country              crossing_points flat_spot      acf #>   <chr>                          <int>     <int>    <dbl> #> 1 Kyrgyz Republic                    3        18  0.909   #> 2 United Arab Emirates               9        18 -0.00320 #> 3 Armenia                            1        17  0.934   #> 4 Jordan                             3         3  0.846   #> 5 Rwanda                             7         3  0.539   #> 6 West Bank and Gaza                 8         3  0.608 pm_diagnostic_metrics <- compute_diagnostic_indices(pm_data, group_var = "region") pm_diagnostic_metrics_group <- add_group_info(                     metric_summary = pm_diagnostic_metrics,                     pm_data             )

title: wdiexplorer
text: third stage workflow utilises visual summaries detect potentially interesting features within panel data. package offers five core functions, two static plot functions: plot_metric_distribution(), plot_metric_partition() three interactive plot functions: plot_data_trajectories(), plot_parallel_coords(), plot_metric_linkview().

title: wdiexplorer
text: plot_metric_distribution() generates distribution plot set diagnostic indices selected metric(s). default, distribution(s) ungrouped; group_var specified, distributions grouped levels within panel. one metric specified metric_var, single panel displayed. function takes two main arguments: data frame containing computed diagnostic metrics pre-defined grouping information metric_summary; variable, colour_var whose levels mapped distinct colours resulting dot plot. Distribution diagnostic indices panel represents different metric. shows spread metric values across countries, dot representing country coloured region. Countries North America region stand lowest within-group average dissimilarity highest silhouette width values. Figure shows ungrouped distribution diagnostic indices. metric presented separate panel, dot per country metric value dots coloured region. figure reveals distinct distributional patterns across indices. instance, country average dissimilarity smoothness measures rightly skewed countries low values. indicates majority countries differ minimally one another tends follow smooth, gradual changes time (based smoothness measures). Distribution diagnostic indices grouped region. panel displays metric, countries organised region facilitate within group comparisons. plot reveals region-specific patterns outliers. Sub-Saharan Africa East Asia & Pacific regions show wider spread North America region closely knitted. grouped distribution plot shows distribution diagnostic indices grouped region. ungrouped version presents countries together individual dots single distribution per metric, grouped version organises countries region, making easier compare within group metric values across regions. Across regions, country average dissimilarity metric consistently right-skewed, though Sub-Saharan Africa Middle East & North Africa contain notable outliers deviate substantially countries region. similar pattern observed within-group average dissimilarity metric. silhouette width panel, countries Latin America & Caribbean Sub-Saharan Africa negative values, suggesting temporal patterns may aligned countries outside assigned groups three countries North America region highest silhouette width values. Users can also generate distribution plot specific metric(s) choice. Distribution linearity metric coloured region. Distribution linearity curvature metrics coloured region grouped region.
code: # ungrouped distribution plot plot_metric_distribution(       metric_summary = pm_diagnostic_metrics_group,        colour_var = "region"       ) # grouped distribution plot plot_metric_distribution(       metric_summary = pm_diagnostic_metrics_group,        colour_var = "region",       group_var = "region"       ) # ungrouped distribution plot for linearity metric plot_metric_distribution(         metric_summary = pm_diagnostic_metrics_group,          metric_var = "linearity",         colour_var = "region"     ) # grouped distribution plot for linearity and curvature metrics plot_metric_distribution(         metric_summary = pm_diagnostic_metrics_group,          metric_var = c("linearity", "curvature"),         colour_var = "region",         group_var = "region"     )

title: Explore World Development Indicators Data
text: wdiexplorer package provides collection indices visualisation tools exploratory analysis country-level panel data World Development Indicators (WDI, world bank collection development indicators) using WDI R package effectively source store data locally. package name acronym captures core functionality: World Development Indicators Explorer. two main goals wdiexplorer package: collection diagnostic indices characterise panel data behaviour. Group-informed exploration country-level panel data leverage pre-defined groupings data interactive visuals capture behavioural patterns highlight group-based features. World Development Indicators Explorer R

Plot of data trajectories — plot_data_trajectories
text: Generates trajectory country data series supports two plot modes: display series uniformly mode highlight countries metric values within specified percentile. mode can rendered two versions: ungrouped grouped. Hovering highlighted line displays corresponding country name metric value

title: Plot of data trajectories — plot_data_trajectories
code: plot_data_trajectories(   wdi_data,   index = NULL,   group_var = NULL,   metric_summary = NULL,   metric_var = NULL,   percentile = 0.95 )

title: Plot of data trajectories — plot_data_trajectories
text: wdi_data data frame indicator data generated get_wdi_data index character string specifying indicator code Defaults NULL group_var grouping variable WDI data set (e.g., "region" "income") Default NULL NULL, trajectories ungrouped specified, trajectories grouped levels variable metric_summary data frame containing computed diagnostic metrics pre-defined grouping information, generated passing output diagnostic metrics function add_group_info Defaults NULL. NULL, data trajectories plotted per country series specified, highlight countries using colour palette based metric threshold metric_var Character string specifying metric variable name metric_summary plot percentile percentile threshold (0 1) highlighting countries based metric values Defaults 0.95, meaning countries fall within top 5% metric_var values

what: Plot distribution(s) of diagnostic metric(s) — plot_metric_distribution
title: Plot distribution(s) of diagnostic metric(s) — plot_metric_distribution
text: Generates faceted ggplot displaying distribution either selected metric(s) set diagnostic indices. default, distribution(s) ungrouped; group_var specified, distributions grouped levels within panel. one metric specified metric_var, single panel displayed.

title: Plot distribution(s) of diagnostic metric(s) — plot_metric_distribution
code: plot_metric_distribution(   metric_summary,   colour_var,   metric_var = NULL,   group_var = NULL )

title: Plot distribution(s) of diagnostic metric(s) — plot_metric_distribution
text: metric_summary data frame containing computed diagnostic metrics pre-defined grouping information, generated passing output diagnostic metrics function add_group_info colour_var variable metric_summary data frame whose levels mapped distinct colours resulting plot metric_var Character string vector character strings specifying metric variable name(s) metric_summary plot NULL (default), distributions plotted metric variables metric_summary specified, distribution specified metric(s) plotted group_var grouping variable WDI data set (e.g., "region" "income") Default NULL NULL, distributions ungrouped specified, distributions grouped levels variable

title: Plot distribution(s) of diagnostic metric(s) — plot_metric_distribution
text: ggplot object displaying either ungrouped grouped distribution metric(s) metric_summary. metric displayed separate facet panel; one metric specified, single panel shown.

title: Plot distribution(s) of diagnostic metric(s) — plot_metric_distribution
code: pm_diagnostic_metrics <- compute_diagnostic_indices(pm_data, group_var = "region") pm_diagnostic_metrics_group <- add_group_info(metric_summary = pm_diagnostic_metrics,pm_data) plot_metric_distribution(pm_diagnostic_metrics_group, colour_var = "region", group_var = "region")

what: Plot of diagnostic metrics linked to data trajectories — plot_metric_linkview
title: Plot of diagnostic metrics linked to data trajectories — plot_metric_linkview
text: Creates interactive plot linking scatterplot two selected metrics data trajectories. scatterplot showing relationship specified metrics presented one panel, data trajectories presented another panel. Hovering point scatterplot highlights corresponding trajectory country name, vice versa.

title: Plot of diagnostic metrics linked to data trajectories — plot_metric_linkview
code: plot_metric_linkview(   wdi_data,   index = NULL,   metric_summary,   metric_var,   group_var = NULL )

Plot of metric values partitioned by grouping variable — plot_metric_partition

title: Plot of metric values partitioned by grouping variable — plot_metric_partition
